WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.540 align:middle line:90%


00:00:13.540 --> 00:00:14.540 align:middle line:90%
>> You have to see this.

00:00:14.540 --> 00:00:15.240 align:middle line:90%
Did you see this?

00:00:15.240 --> 00:00:16.040 align:middle line:90%
Did you see this?

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:17.390 align:middle line:90%
This is so cool.

00:00:17.390 --> 00:00:20.570 align:middle line:84%
>> It was just a
pulsating thing.

00:00:20.570 --> 00:00:23.270 align:middle line:90%
>> Wispy flower effect.

00:00:23.270 --> 00:00:24.560 align:middle line:90%
>> I was just thrilled.

00:00:24.560 --> 00:00:27.150 align:middle line:84%
>> It was like the Pac-Man
coming and taking these little

00:00:27.150 --> 00:00:27.950 align:middle line:90%
bites.

00:00:27.950 --> 00:00:29.390 align:middle line:90%
>> This is not a normal thing.

00:00:29.390 --> 00:00:31.160 align:middle line:84%
This is not something
you see every day.

00:00:31.160 --> 00:00:34.577 align:middle line:84%
>> Something very strange,
very unusual, is happening.

00:00:34.577 --> 00:00:37.160 align:middle line:84%
>> The animals were freaking out
because they didn't know what

00:00:37.160 --> 00:00:38.150 align:middle line:90%
was happening.

00:00:38.150 --> 00:00:40.640 align:middle line:84%
>> Even though we all knew
exactly what was going

00:00:40.640 --> 00:00:44.630 align:middle line:84%
to happen, to see it in real
life was just unbelievable.

00:00:44.630 --> 00:00:57.820 align:middle line:90%


00:00:57.820 --> 00:01:00.600 align:middle line:10%
>> There is nothing
like a total eclipse.

00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:03.450 align:middle line:10%
>> It is the most mind-boggling
thing you're ever going to see

00:01:03.450 --> 00:01:04.830 align:middle line:10%
in nature.

00:01:04.830 --> 00:01:07.530 align:middle line:10%
>> There are not many things
that a person sees in his

00:01:07.530 --> 00:01:12.240 align:middle line:10%
lifetime that are as singular
as a total solar eclipse.

00:01:12.240 --> 00:01:15.000 align:middle line:10%
>> Incredible sense of awe.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:17.910 align:middle line:10%
>> And all these people
started arriving and setting up

00:01:17.910 --> 00:01:21.690 align:middle line:10%
telescopes, every kind of
scientific gadget you could

00:01:21.690 --> 00:01:22.630 align:middle line:10%
imagine.

00:01:22.630 --> 00:01:25.230 align:middle line:10%
And I thought, well,
this is interesting.

00:01:25.230 --> 00:01:28.680 align:middle line:10%
>> The Earth is really fortunate
to be able to see an eclipse.

00:01:28.680 --> 00:01:32.130 align:middle line:84%
There is not the
geometry for a person

00:01:32.130 --> 00:01:34.920 align:middle line:84%
to witness a total solar
eclipse on any other planet

00:01:34.920 --> 00:01:36.390 align:middle line:90%
in the solar system.

00:01:36.390 --> 00:01:41.010 align:middle line:84%
Earth's moon is-- even though
400 times smaller than the sun,

00:01:41.010 --> 00:01:42.940 align:middle line:90%
it's 400 times closer.

00:01:42.940 --> 00:01:45.300 align:middle line:84%
And so that geometry
allows us to witness

00:01:45.300 --> 00:01:46.900 align:middle line:90%
a total solar eclipse.

00:01:46.900 --> 00:01:49.950 align:middle line:10%
>> And you get to really feel
this ethereal effect of having

00:01:49.950 --> 00:01:53.310 align:middle line:10%
the sun go dark in
the middle of the day.

00:01:53.310 --> 00:01:56.400 align:middle line:10%
>> A solar eclipse only
happens at new moon phase.

00:01:56.400 --> 00:01:58.560 align:middle line:10%
And it's when the new
moon goes directly

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:02.400 align:middle line:10%
in front of the disc of the
sun and casts its shadow

00:02:02.400 --> 00:02:05.820 align:middle line:10%
onto the surface of the Earth,
and effectively blocks out

00:02:05.820 --> 00:02:07.950 align:middle line:10%
the sunlight for a
short period of time.

00:02:07.950 --> 00:02:10.500 align:middle line:84%
>> The new moon is when
the side facing the earth,

00:02:10.500 --> 00:02:14.190 align:middle line:84%
the near side, is not
illuminated by the sun.

00:02:14.190 --> 00:02:16.140 align:middle line:84%
The only part of the
moon that's illuminated

00:02:16.140 --> 00:02:19.160 align:middle line:84%
by the sun at new moon is
the far side of the moon.

00:02:19.160 --> 00:02:20.950 align:middle line:84%
But there's a new moon
every single month,

00:02:20.950 --> 00:02:22.800 align:middle line:84%
so why don't we see an
eclipse every month?

00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:25.260 align:middle line:84%
>> And that's because the
orbit of the moon is tilted

00:02:25.260 --> 00:02:29.520 align:middle line:84%
or inclined compared to the
Earth's orbit around the sun.

00:02:29.520 --> 00:02:32.950 align:middle line:84%
>> So sometimes the moon passes
above the sun in the sky,

00:02:32.950 --> 00:02:35.800 align:middle line:84%
sometimes it passes
below the sun in the sky.

00:02:35.800 --> 00:02:39.030 align:middle line:84%
So if the new moon is below the
sun, we won't get an eclipse.

00:02:39.030 --> 00:02:42.300 align:middle line:84%
>> Only when the orbit of the
moon lines up with the orbit

00:02:42.300 --> 00:02:44.910 align:middle line:84%
of the Earth in
the new moon phase,

00:02:44.910 --> 00:02:47.580 align:middle line:84%
that we're able to get to
have a total solar eclipse.

00:02:47.580 --> 00:02:50.370 align:middle line:10%
>> We actually get a total
eclipse about once every one

00:02:50.370 --> 00:02:54.150 align:middle line:10%
to two years, but they're
only visible from a very small

00:02:54.150 --> 00:02:56.160 align:middle line:10%
fraction of the Earth's surface.

00:02:56.160 --> 00:02:58.100 align:middle line:10%
>> Now it's not always
a total solar eclipse,

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:00.600 align:middle line:10%
because sometimes the moon is
a little bit farther away from

00:03:00.600 --> 00:03:03.660 align:middle line:10%
the Earth, and so you'll
get what's called an annular

00:03:03.660 --> 00:03:06.970 align:middle line:10%
eclipse, which is when we
have a ring around the edge

00:03:06.970 --> 00:03:07.770 align:middle line:10%
of the moon.

00:03:07.770 --> 00:03:11.400 align:middle line:84%
>> Some of the sun still
peeks its way around the moon.

00:03:11.400 --> 00:03:14.490 align:middle line:84%
And that is because our orbits
are not perfectly circular.

00:03:14.490 --> 00:03:16.930 align:middle line:84%
We are actually
elliptical orbits,

00:03:16.930 --> 00:03:19.050 align:middle line:84%
so the Earth is a
little off-center.

00:03:19.050 --> 00:03:21.630 align:middle line:84%
That means there are times
when the moon is a bit closer

00:03:21.630 --> 00:03:23.970 align:middle line:84%
to the Earth, and there
are times when the moon is

00:03:23.970 --> 00:03:26.280 align:middle line:90%
a bit farther from the Earth.

00:03:26.280 --> 00:03:29.580 align:middle line:84%
This changes how big
the moon appears to us.

00:03:29.580 --> 00:03:31.710 align:middle line:84%
And when the moon's a
little too far away,

00:03:31.710 --> 00:03:33.880 align:middle line:90%
it appears a little too small.

00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:37.020 align:middle line:84%
And so it does not block
the entire face of the sun.

00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:39.560 align:middle line:84%
>> And so you'll have a ring
around it or an annulus.

00:03:39.560 --> 00:03:42.840 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes that's referred
to as a ring of fire.

00:03:42.840 --> 00:03:46.530 align:middle line:84%
>> But the interesting thing
is that our moon is very slowly

00:03:46.530 --> 00:03:49.890 align:middle line:84%
drifting away from the Earth
at about a rate of one inch per

00:03:49.890 --> 00:03:51.130 align:middle line:90%
year.

00:03:51.130 --> 00:03:53.370 align:middle line:84%
So that means, if
human beings are still

00:03:53.370 --> 00:03:57.240 align:middle line:84%
living on this planet hundreds
of thousands of years from now,

00:03:57.240 --> 00:03:59.640 align:middle line:84%
they won't get to see
a total solar eclipse.

00:03:59.640 --> 00:04:03.090 align:middle line:84%
They will only get to
see an annular eclipse.

00:04:03.090 --> 00:04:06.960 align:middle line:84%
>> So because of this changing
in distance with the moon,

00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:10.620 align:middle line:84%
up until this point human
history has been pretty lucky.

00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:14.280 align:middle line:10%
The moon has appeared as big
as or bigger than the sun

00:04:14.280 --> 00:04:17.070 align:middle line:10%
and allowed a total
blocking of that sunlight.

00:04:17.070 --> 00:04:19.140 align:middle line:10%
So it's a very
magical time for us.

00:04:19.140 --> 00:04:22.620 align:middle line:10%
We need to keep observing these
total eclipses as long as we

00:04:22.620 --> 00:04:25.560 align:middle line:10%
can, recording the
data and the images

00:04:25.560 --> 00:04:28.140 align:middle line:10%
that we get from them
really for posterity, so

00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:30.060 align:middle line:10%
that the future can
see what we used

00:04:30.060 --> 00:04:31.230 align:middle line:10%
to observe here in the past.

00:04:31.230 --> 00:04:45.740 align:middle line:90%


00:04:45.740 --> 00:04:48.980 align:middle line:84%
>> There were things about
the solar eclipse that really

00:04:48.980 --> 00:04:50.360 align:middle line:90%
surprised me.

00:04:50.360 --> 00:04:53.180 align:middle line:84%
>> About 15 to 20
minutes before totality,

00:04:53.180 --> 00:04:57.650 align:middle line:84%
the light became unlike
anything I'd ever seen before.

00:04:57.650 --> 00:05:01.220 align:middle line:10%
>> As the sun becomes more
obscured and the light is more

00:05:01.220 --> 00:05:04.100 align:middle line:10%
of a narrow focused light, the
shadows all around you will

00:05:04.100 --> 00:05:06.470 align:middle line:10%
become much more
defined, much more crisp.

00:05:06.470 --> 00:05:09.470 align:middle line:10%
>> The light streaming through
the leaves on a tree will

00:05:09.470 --> 00:05:12.530 align:middle line:10%
produce crescent images of
the sun on the ground below

00:05:12.530 --> 00:05:15.830 align:middle line:10%
the tree during all the
partial phases of the eclipse,

00:05:15.830 --> 00:05:18.290 align:middle line:10%
hundreds of them, as light
goes through those really small

00:05:18.290 --> 00:05:19.090 align:middle line:10%
spaces.

00:05:19.090 --> 00:05:23.030 align:middle line:10%
>> I took a picture of the
ground underneath a tree.

00:05:23.030 --> 00:05:25.910 align:middle line:84%
The spaces between the leaves
were acting like little pinhole

00:05:25.910 --> 00:05:28.520 align:middle line:84%
cameras, and there
were just a number

00:05:28.520 --> 00:05:30.330 align:middle line:90%
of those images on the ground.

00:05:30.330 --> 00:05:55.160 align:middle line:90%


00:05:55.160 --> 00:05:58.450 align:middle line:84%
>> So something that's fun to
do also is to look for something

00:05:58.450 --> 00:06:01.150 align:middle line:84%
that will block the light and
still allow points of light

00:06:01.150 --> 00:06:02.170 align:middle line:90%
to go through it.

00:06:02.170 --> 00:06:05.040 align:middle line:84%
>> Anything with small
holes in it will work.

00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:07.670 align:middle line:84%
>> Colanders will create
beautiful patterns.

00:06:07.670 --> 00:06:10.640 align:middle line:84%
>> A strainer-type spoon
with circular holes.

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:13.990 align:middle line:84%
>> A button, a Ritz
cracker, straw hats,

00:06:13.990 --> 00:06:16.870 align:middle line:84%
anything that will allow some
light to come through but still

00:06:16.870 --> 00:06:19.865 align:middle line:84%
cast a shadow, will be a fun
way to watch the progress

00:06:19.865 --> 00:06:20.665 align:middle line:90%
of the eclipse.

00:06:20.665 --> 00:06:29.198 align:middle line:90%


00:06:29.198 --> 00:06:31.740 align:middle line:84%
>> Even before totality, you'll
notice that there is a change

00:06:31.740 --> 00:06:32.540 align:middle line:90%
in temperature.

00:06:32.540 --> 00:06:34.440 align:middle line:84%
>> I felt the
temperature change.

00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:36.870 align:middle line:84%
>> You can expect the
temperature to drop anywhere

00:06:36.870 --> 00:06:40.260 align:middle line:84%
from 10 to 15 degrees
when it is in totality.

00:06:40.260 --> 00:06:43.020 align:middle line:84%
The animals notice that
the light is decreasing

00:06:43.020 --> 00:06:45.090 align:middle line:84%
and many of them will
change their behavior.

00:06:45.090 --> 00:06:47.190 align:middle line:84%
Chickens may decide
to go back to roost.

00:06:47.190 --> 00:06:48.930 align:middle line:90%
Cows may bed down.

00:06:48.930 --> 00:06:50.430 align:middle line:90%
Crickets may start chirping.

00:06:50.430 --> 00:06:54.300 align:middle line:84%
Birds oftentimes stop singing,
unless it's a night bird.

00:06:54.300 --> 00:06:55.830 align:middle line:90%
So an owl might start hooting.

00:06:55.830 --> 00:06:57.930 align:middle line:84%
So if you have
animals around you,

00:06:57.930 --> 00:06:59.580 align:middle line:84%
pay attention to
what they're doing.

00:06:59.580 --> 00:07:02.100 align:middle line:84%
>> Those are all kinds of
phenomena to watch for that

00:07:02.100 --> 00:07:05.410 align:middle line:84%
aren't actually part of the
eclipse but kind of an effect

00:07:05.410 --> 00:07:06.210 align:middle line:90%
of the eclipse.

00:07:06.210 --> 00:07:09.855 align:middle line:90%


00:07:09.855 --> 00:07:10.655 align:middle line:90%
>> One minute.

00:07:10.655 --> 00:07:16.010 align:middle line:90%


00:07:16.010 --> 00:07:18.770 align:middle line:10%
>> Shadow bands are caused by
the focused light from our sun

00:07:18.770 --> 00:07:20.330 align:middle line:10%
coming through our atmosphere.

00:07:20.330 --> 00:07:22.050 align:middle line:10%
And our atmosphere
is like a fluid,

00:07:22.050 --> 00:07:25.010 align:middle line:10%
and so it is
refracting the light.

00:07:25.010 --> 00:07:28.180 align:middle line:84%
And so that's why they appear
like ripples on the ground.

00:07:28.180 --> 00:07:36.480 align:middle line:90%
>> [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:07:36.480 --> 00:07:39.230 align:middle line:84%
>> Our atmosphere acts like
a fluid just like the water

00:07:39.230 --> 00:07:40.680 align:middle line:90%
in a swimming pool.

00:07:40.680 --> 00:07:43.310 align:middle line:84%
If you've ever stood next
to an outdoor swimming pool

00:07:43.310 --> 00:07:45.403 align:middle line:84%
during the daytime,
you'll notice

00:07:45.403 --> 00:07:46.820 align:middle line:84%
that at the bottom
of the pool you

00:07:46.820 --> 00:07:49.160 align:middle line:84%
can see shadows and
bright bands moving

00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:51.440 align:middle line:84%
as the surface of
the water moves.

00:07:51.440 --> 00:07:53.600 align:middle line:84%
The same thing happens
with our atmosphere.

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:55.370 align:middle line:84%
Our atmosphere is
constantly moving,

00:07:55.370 --> 00:07:57.620 align:middle line:84%
so there's areas where the
air is a little more dense,

00:07:57.620 --> 00:07:59.810 align:middle line:84%
some places where it's
a little less dense.

00:07:59.810 --> 00:08:02.270 align:middle line:84%
And so we see
brightness, and we also

00:08:02.270 --> 00:08:04.620 align:middle line:90%
see those contrasting shadows.

00:08:04.620 --> 00:08:07.490 align:middle line:84%
>> It's very similar to
the effect when you look up

00:08:07.490 --> 00:08:10.080 align:middle line:84%
to a very bright star and our
atmosphere causes the star

00:08:10.080 --> 00:08:10.880 align:middle line:90%
to twinkle.

00:08:10.880 --> 00:08:18.760 align:middle line:90%


00:08:18.760 --> 00:08:23.110 align:middle line:84%
>> And we also get to see
some interesting nuances like

00:08:23.110 --> 00:08:26.830 align:middle line:84%
the Baily's beads, which occur
because the lunar surface is

00:08:26.830 --> 00:08:28.870 align:middle line:90%
not perfectly smooth.

00:08:28.870 --> 00:08:31.870 align:middle line:84%
The moon has
mountains and valleys,

00:08:31.870 --> 00:08:36.640 align:middle line:84%
and when the solar light tries
to bend its way past the moon,

00:08:36.640 --> 00:08:39.429 align:middle line:84%
naturally some of the
mountains will block that light

00:08:39.429 --> 00:08:42.340 align:middle line:84%
and some light will make its
way through between the valleys.

00:08:42.340 --> 00:08:46.450 align:middle line:84%
>> Baily's beads is a phenomenon
discovered by Francis Baily

00:08:46.450 --> 00:08:49.660 align:middle line:84%
in the 1800s, where he was
observing a solar eclipse

00:08:49.660 --> 00:08:53.560 align:middle line:84%
and he noticed the last sunlight
right before totality is

00:08:53.560 --> 00:08:57.100 align:middle line:84%
streaming between the mountain
peaks on the edge of the moon.

00:08:57.100 --> 00:08:59.830 align:middle line:84%
And to him they looked like
a string of bright beads,

00:08:59.830 --> 00:09:01.720 align:middle line:90%
and the name stuck.

00:09:01.720 --> 00:09:05.350 align:middle line:84%
So when we see that,
we're seeing the last rays

00:09:05.350 --> 00:09:09.850 align:middle line:84%
of sunlight pouring between
the mountain peaks and valleys

00:09:09.850 --> 00:09:11.620 align:middle line:90%
on the surface of the moon.

00:09:11.620 --> 00:09:13.690 align:middle line:10%
And they're only
visible right before

00:09:13.690 --> 00:09:16.030 align:middle line:10%
and right after totality,
and they're only

00:09:16.030 --> 00:09:17.990 align:middle line:10%
visible for a few seconds.

00:09:17.990 --> 00:09:21.130 align:middle line:84%
And we see that last
little bit of light

00:09:21.130 --> 00:09:23.560 align:middle line:84%
just as we would see a
sunset between mountain peaks

00:09:23.560 --> 00:09:24.380 align:middle line:90%
here on Earth.

00:09:24.380 --> 00:09:25.180 align:middle line:90%
>> Oh, my God.

00:09:25.180 --> 00:09:26.320 align:middle line:10%
That's Baily's beads.

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:28.340 align:middle line:10%
That's what they're
talking about.

00:09:28.340 --> 00:09:31.500 align:middle line:84%
And then the diamond
was gorgeous.

00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:34.610 align:middle line:90%
It just exploded.

00:09:34.610 --> 00:09:35.790 align:middle line:90%
>> Whoa.

00:09:35.790 --> 00:09:36.590 align:middle line:90%
Beautiful.

00:09:36.590 --> 00:09:49.950 align:middle line:90%


00:09:49.950 --> 00:09:52.580 align:middle line:84%
>> And when there is only
one bead of light left,

00:09:52.580 --> 00:09:54.260 align:middle line:90%
that's called the diamond ring.

00:09:54.260 --> 00:09:57.140 align:middle line:84%
>> Something called the
diamond ring effect occurs.

00:09:57.140 --> 00:09:58.910 align:middle line:84%
This is an interesting
side effect

00:09:58.910 --> 00:10:01.610 align:middle line:84%
of the behavior of light,
the fact that light

00:10:01.610 --> 00:10:04.490 align:middle line:84%
behaves as a wave as
well as a particle

00:10:04.490 --> 00:10:07.760 align:middle line:84%
and can therefore
bend around objects.

00:10:07.760 --> 00:10:10.370 align:middle line:84%
In that moment, the
light of the photossphere

00:10:10.370 --> 00:10:13.250 align:middle line:84%
tries to bend its
way around the moon

00:10:13.250 --> 00:10:16.730 align:middle line:84%
and gets concentrated
in a small area.

00:10:16.730 --> 00:10:20.040 align:middle line:84%
Whenever we concentrate
light, we call that a laser.

00:10:20.040 --> 00:10:22.370 align:middle line:84%
And so very truly, the
diamond ring effect

00:10:22.370 --> 00:10:24.777 align:middle line:90%
is a natural-born laser.

00:10:24.777 --> 00:10:26.360 align:middle line:84%
>> Now about the
time that disappears,

00:10:26.360 --> 00:10:28.820 align:middle line:84%
you might have the opportunity
to see the chromosphere.

00:10:28.820 --> 00:10:30.980 align:middle line:84%
It appears pink or
magenta in color,

00:10:30.980 --> 00:10:34.580 align:middle line:84%
which is the next layer
of the sun's atmosphere.

00:10:34.580 --> 00:10:38.300 align:middle line:84%
>> The chromosphere is the
colored layer right above

00:10:38.300 --> 00:10:39.870 align:middle line:90%
the surface of the sun.

00:10:39.870 --> 00:10:41.750 align:middle line:90%
It appears kind of pink.

00:10:41.750 --> 00:10:43.940 align:middle line:10%
It's a layer of the sun
that we don't normally

00:10:43.940 --> 00:10:46.617 align:middle line:10%
see except during a
total solar eclipse.

00:10:46.617 --> 00:10:48.200 align:middle line:84%
>> And in that part
of the atmosphere,

00:10:48.200 --> 00:10:51.650 align:middle line:84%
you will also be able to see,
if you're lucky, a prominence.

00:10:51.650 --> 00:10:55.130 align:middle line:84%
>> Or solar flares, gaseous
material that's erupted off

00:10:55.130 --> 00:10:56.850 align:middle line:90%
the surface of the sun.

